<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-226-267 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 378 404</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Feb 4 1991 v37 n1846 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>John Bardeen, Nobel laureate, dies. (co-inventor of thetransistor) (obituary)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nobel laureate John Bardeen dies in Jan 1991 at the age of 82.andO;Bardeen was the co-inventor of the transistor and twice-recipientof the Nobel Prize for Physics, once for his work on transistorsand the second time for his work on superconductivity.andP;  Bardeenwas part of a three-man team that developed the transistor; othermembers of the team were William Shockley, who died in 1989, andWalter Brattain, who died in 1987.andP;  Bardeen described his role inthe development of the transistor as mostly theoretical.andP;  In 1972,while employed at the University of Illinois, Bardeen originated atheory of low-temperature superconductivity with the help of twograduate students.andP;  He received his bachelor's and master's degreein electrical engineering from the University of Wisconsin and amathematical physics doctorate from Princeton University in 1936.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BiographyInventionsTransistorsDeathSemiconductor industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>